{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"8d9a04fa-f39c-4909-8911-307aeddeeb67","content":"In .NET 10 MAUI, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was deprecated and replaced with the cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property, which also gives you more granular control:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage \n    xmlns=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui\"\n    xmlns:x=\"http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml\"\n    SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n\n    <!-- Your content here -->\n\n</ContentPage>\n```\n\nYou can also target specific edges if needed:\n\n```xml\nSafeAreaRegions=\"Top,Bottom\"\n```\n\nAvailable values: `None`, `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right`, `All`.\n\nThis works cross-platform now (iOS respects Dynamic Island/notch/home indicator, Android respects display cutouts) — no more iOS-specific namespace needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"f8885e19-3b8f-40f0-9c35-dff35f36ef13","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a knowledge question about .NET MAUI changes.\n\nIn .NET 10 (which would be a preview/RC at this point in May 2026), there were changes to how safe area insets are handled. Let me think about what I know:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` was the platform-specific way to handle safe areas on iOS. However, in newer versions of .NET MAUI, there have been changes to this API.\n\n\nI'm trying to recall the specifics of what changed between .NET 9 and .NET 10 for MAUI's safe area handling, but I want to be careful about distinguishing what I'm confident about versus what might be speculation on my part. The newer approach uses `SafeAreaRegions` for more granular control over which edges (Top, Bottom, Left, Right, All, None) respect safe area insets, though I'm uncertain whether the current API is `Page.IgnoreSafeArea` or something else entirely in .NET 10. In .NET 10 MAUI, the safe area handling shifted to a more